<p><cs>\'d8<col><b>Rouge et noir</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr> <ety>[F., red
and black]</ety>, <cd>a game at cards in which persons play against the
owner of the bank; -- so called because the table around which the
players sit has certain compartments colored red and black, upon which
the stakes are deposited.</cd> <rj><au>Hoyle.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rouge
<hw>Rouge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A red amorphous powder consisting of ferric
oxide. It is used in polishing glass, metal, or gems, and as a cosmetic,
etc. Called also <altname>crocus</altname>, <altname>jeweler's
rouge</altname>, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cosmetic used for giving a red color to the cheeks
or lips. The best is prepared from the dried flowers of the safflower,
but it is often made from carmine.</def> <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rouge
<hw>Rouge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rouged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rouging</conjf> .]</vmorph> <def>To paint the face or cheeks with
rouge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouge</ent>⟦br⟧

